---
description: Baseline coding standards for readable, maintainable changes
alwaysApply: true
---

coding-standards:

- Prefer small, focused changes with a clear purpose.
- Use descriptive names for functions, variables, and files.
- When a file defines a class, the filename must use CamelCase (for example, `InvoiceRepository.ts`).
- When a file defines a tool, function, or similar utility, the filename must use kebab-case (for example, `create-invoice-report.ts`).
- Add concise comments only when non-obvious logic needs context.
- Keep user-facing documentation updated when behavior changes.
- Always add a blank line between statements, blocks, and logical sections — never leave code visually suffocated.
- Omit curly braces for single-line `if`, `else`, or any control-flow statement: `if (condition) doSomething()`.
